<font color="#FF0000">A MAN'S WEAPON!</font><br>
<tt>Sun Aug 24 21:05:19 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
No!!! My weapon of choice was not some noisey, foul smelling, M-60 machine gun which required a Spartan's effort just to pack around and keep clean...a cumbersome, unwieldly instrument.  Nor was it some hardware store nightmare wrapped in Reynolds Wrap... sucking up the tax payer's dollars at the speed of sound, converting precious petroleum resources into ear splitting sounds and foul odors.<br><br>
My weapon of choice was a P-38 can opener!<br><br>
I remember the crash and the twisted wreckage... I was trapped.  Barely able to move my head, I manuevered my head into position and grasped my P-38 between my clenched teeth.  I had some difficulty unfolding it, at first... It had deflected a .51 cal Russian round from my bare, bronze colored, naked, masculine chest... and was slightly bent.  Nevertheless, I managed to cut my self free of the crushed cockpit and escape... moments before a large contingent of NVA, VC, Chi-Coms, two evangalist and one hippie arrived and began fighting over my new camera.<br>
Lying on my back, with both arms and both legs broken I used my highly polished P-38 and the tropic sun to flash a morse code message to Silent Warrior, who was cruising at altitude with his oxygen mask off (looking for that euphoric feeling.)  I had some difficulty... I had forgotten how to spell S.O.S. and kept spelling Spam...Spam..Spam!<br>
Distraught, I rolled onto my belly and dug my trusty P-38 into the hard laterite dirt and drug myself to the nearest river... fifty clicks up hill through a bamboo thicket.<br>
One of the bead links in my neck chain was actually a tiny radio (designed and built by &quot;No Sweat Chet&quot; somewhere up north.)  I turned it on... but could only pick up &quot;Good Morning... Viet Nam,&quot;  ... they were playing &quot;...Peeping and  a'hiding...slipping and a'sliding...&quot;<br>
I decided to back track and set up an ambush.  You can't imagine the horror of cutting a Commie hippie advisor's throat with a P-38... it was awful... cutting through those layers of beads... while he kept screaming, &quot;I knew I should have gone to Canada!&quot;<br>
Later, I fashioned a crude raft from bamboo and floated to safety.  Far in the rear I encountered a Marine platoon who were trying open a can of Ham and Lima beans with the front sight of an M-60.  I just smiled through my agonizing pain an floated on by humming &quot;Over hill..over dale.. as we hit the dusty trail... as those caisons go rolling along..&quot; and &quot;Put Silver Wings on my son's chest... make him one of America's best...&quot;<br><br>
This IS NOT a TRUE STORY... but it SHOULD BE!<br><br>
Mustang Two Four
